  <!-- FAQ -->
  <h2 id="faq">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
  <div class="space-y-6 mb-6">
    <div class="bg-white rounded-xl border border-gray-200 p-5 shadow-sm">
      <h3 class="text-base font-semibold text-navy mb-2">What is back pressure in a disc centrifuge?</h3>
      <p class="text-text-light text-sm">Back pressure is the positive pressure maintained at the light-phase (liquid) outlet of a disc centrifuge. It positions the liquid interface between the light and heavy phases at the correct radius within the bowl, preventing heavy phase from contaminating the light phase outlet or vice versa.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="bg-white rounded-xl border border-gray-200 p-5 shadow-sm">
      <h3 class="text-base font-semibold text-navy mb-2">How do I set the correct back pressure in a disc centrifuge?</h3>
      <p class="text-text-light text-sm">Back pressure is set by selecting the correct gravity disc (interface disc) size. Larger gravity discs increase back pressure and move the interface inward; smaller discs decrease back pressure and move it outward. Match the gravity disc to the density difference between your light and heavy phases using the centrifuge manufacturer's gravity disc selection chart.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="bg-white rounded-xl border border-gray-200 p-5 shadow-sm">
      <h3 class="text-base font-semibold text-navy mb-2">What happens if centrifuge back pressure is too high or too low?</h3>
      <p class="text-text-light text-sm">Too low: the interface moves outward past the gravity disc, causing heavy phase (water, sludge) to flood the light phase outlet — the centrifuge loses its liquid seal. Too high: the interface moves inward, causing light phase to overflow into the heavy phase outlet. Both conditions degrade separation quality.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="bg-white rounded-xl border border-gray-200 p-5 shadow-sm">
      <h3 class="text-base font-semibold text-navy mb-2">What is a gravity disc in a disc centrifuge?</h3>
      <p class="text-text-light text-sm">A gravity disc (also called a regulating ring or interface disc) is a removable disc with a precisely sized central hole in the light phase outlet path. By selecting the correct hole diameter, the operator controls the heavy liquid phase depth in the bowl, which determines where the oil-water interface sits within the disc stack.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="bg-white rounded-xl border border-gray-200 p-5 shadow-sm">
      <h3 class="text-base font-semibold text-navy mb-2">How do I know if my centrifuge back pressure needs adjustment?</h3>
      <p class="text-text-light text-sm">Signs of incorrect back pressure include: water or sludge in the light phase (oil) outlet, oil in the heavy phase (water) outlet, turbid or milky clarified product, frequent <a href="/disc-stack-centrifuge-liquid-seal-break/" class="text-navy font-semibold hover:text-gold transition-colors">liquid seal breaks</a>, and inconsistent separation quality despite stable feed conditions. Sample both outlets and check for cross-contamination.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
